This paper discusses the identification of influential people in online social networks, which falls under the category of social network analysis. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also proposes a new measure of centrality that models the effect of limited attention on epidemic diffusion, which involves analyzing the spread of information in a network, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely sub-category as well. Additionally, the paper discusses the evaluation of the proposed measure on real-world online social networks, which involves using machine learning techniques, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper also discusses the potential security implications of identifying influential people in social networks, making cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy) a possible sub-category.
